A plausible picture of the calcined sample can be attempted by tentatively hypothesizing what takes place during the heating process.
It is known that CrO3 decomposes at relatively low temperatures to give the more stable a-Cr2O3 oxide.
Therefore, at increasing temperature, only a fraction of initial Cr, strongly interacting with the support,retains the VI oxidation state (actually VI and V,especially in the case of the zirconia support) and forms a surface chromate. If the initial CrVI exceeds this amount, one would expect that the excess decom- poses to give the more stable a-chromia, which is known to undergo extreme sintering at our calcination temperature (973 K). The fact that CrIII species, other than a-chromia, are found points again to an inter- vention of the support. CrIII species giving rise to the ESR d-signal are linked to the ability of the alumina support to dissolve some CrIII. As for CrIII species detected as the ESR b-signal, one can speculate their origin from Cr less strongly interacting with the support than the Cr leading to surface chromate.
The interaction of this fraction of chromium would be strong enough to prevent segregation of large a- chromia crystallites, but not so strong to hinder aggre- gation into small CrIII oxide clusters on the surface of the support.
The above picture is rendered more complex if one considers the dynamic evolution that takes place upon high temperature treatment. Whereas a-Cr2O3 is not likely to spread over the surface, it is nevertheless possible that, at some stage of the calcination in air,chromia particles not sufciently grown and still in contact with the support undergo oxidation to CrO3, and subsequently spread because of the much lower surface tension. Cr dispersed species are thus formed.
Interestingly, silica has a particular behaviour in this respect. Our results show that this support is able to strongly retain an amount (small, if compared to its large surface area) of Cr as CrVI but if this amount is exceeded, the excess gives rise to large a-chromia particles, in agreement with published results [16].Previous work on dilute ZC, AC and SC systems [1 3] indicated that: (i) the catalytic activity for alkane dehydrogenation was proportional to the Cr content;(ii) the dehydrogenation rate per Cr atom (i.e. the turnover frequency per Cr atom) was substantially higher for ZC than either AC or SC; (iii) the turnover frequency per Cr atom for AC and SC was comparable to that of a-chromia, provided that in this latter case only the surface Cr atoms were taken into account (specically, the value 10.84 atoms nm2, from crys- tallographic data [24], was used for a-chromia).
